This paper belongs to the arXiv CS sub-category of social and information networks (cs.SI) as it focuses on the study of longitudinal social networks and their evolution over time. It also relates to the sub-category of social and economic systems (cs.SOC) as it explores the dynamics of social networks and their impact on behaviour and belief formation. Additionally, the paper involves the use of network science and data analysis techniques, which are relevant to the sub-categories of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) and cybersecurity (cs.CYBER). Finally, the paper discusses the implications of its findings for future research, which is relevant to the sub-category of cryptography and security (cs.CR).
